# .env.local.example — RESLU Spec System
# Copy this file to .env.local and fill in real values.
# .env.local is git-ignored — never commit real credentials.

# ── Supabase ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Create a project at supabase.com (Pro plan recommended — see
# BUILD-SPEC.md; the free tier pauses after 7 days of inactivity).
# Values come from Supabase Dashboard → Settings → API.
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL=https://your-project-ref.supabase.co
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=your-anon-key-here
SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY=your-service-role-key-here

# ── Monday.com ───────────────────────────────────────────────
# The token referenced in the original brief PDF is considered
# compromised (it was pasted in plaintext into a shared document).
# Rotate it in Monday.com before use and paste the new value here.
MONDAY_API_TOKEN=

# ── Gmail API (aria@reslu.com.au) ───────────────────────────
# Same rotation requirement as above — these credentials were also
# exposed in the original brief PDF. Not required for Week 1.
GMAIL_CLIENT_ID=
GMAIL_CLIENT_SECRET=
ARIA_GMAIL_REFRESH_TOKEN=
GMAIL_TOKEN_URI=https://oauth2.googleapis.com/token

# ── App URL ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Local dev:
NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL=http://localhost:3000
# Production (set after deploying to Vercel):
# NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL=https://spec.reslu.com.au

# ── Cron (digest flush) ──────────────────────────────────────
# vercel.json schedules POST /api/digest/flush hourly via Vercel Cron.
# Set this to a long random string in Vercel's project environment
# variables (Production) — Vercel sends it as
# `authorization: Bearer <value>` on scheduled invocations, which the
# route checks explicitly (see app/api/digest/flush/route.ts). Leave
# blank in local dev; the manual/session-authenticated trigger keeps
# working either way. Generate one with e.g. `openssl rand -hex 32`.
CRON_SECRET=

# ── Website lead intake (reslu.com.au /begin) ─────────────
# Shared bearer secret for POST /api/leads/intake — the website's
# Vercel function (reslu-site/api/enquiry.js) sends it as
# `Authorization: Bearer <value>`. Set the SAME value here and as
# CRM_WEBHOOK_SECRET on the website's Vercel project (which also needs
# CRM_WEBHOOK_URL=https://spec.reslu.com.au/api/leads/intake).
# Generate with `openssl rand -hex 24`. Unset = route rejects all
# requests (503) — fail closed. See RESLU-Spec-Lead-Intake.md.
LEAD_INTAKE_SECRET=

# ── Aria (OpenClaw agent) — Week 10 ──────────────────────────
# Aria's own Supabase user (profile "Aria (agent)", role admin — see
# BUILD-SPEC.md §"Agent control — Aria"). Used by:
#   - mcp/ (the MCP server, on the mini — mcp/.env, NOT this file)
#   - any launchd automation script calling the REST API directly
# These three are NOT read by the Next.js app itself — the app has no
# code path that logs in as Aria — they exist purely so the mini's
# automations/mcp server have one documented place to source them.
# Never committed; rotate via Supabase Auth if compromised.
ARIA_EMAIL=aria@reslu.com.au
ARIA_PASSWORD=
SPEC_URL=https://spec.reslu.com.au

# ── Monday leads import (one-time, Week 10) ──────────────────
# Used only by scripts/import-monday-leads.mjs, run manually on the
# mini. Reuses MONDAY_API_TOKEN above; also needs the Supabase values
# above (service role key, for the upsert). See docs/API.md and the
# script's own header comment for usage.

# ── Resend (site-visit lifecycle emails) ──────────────────────
# docs/RESLU-Spec-Visit-Emails-Brief.md: visit-confirmation /
# visit-reminder emails, sent via a plain fetch to Resend's REST API
# (no SDK dependency) from lib/visit-emails.ts. Create a SECOND API key
# in the SAME Resend account as the website's own key — do NOT reuse
# the website's key (the brief is explicit on this) — the domain is
# already verified there. Unset = every send/queue attempt no-ops
# cleanly, logged as an email_sends row with status 'skipped' and
# detail.reason 'no RESEND_API_KEY' (see lib/visit-emails.ts's
# sendViaResend doc comment) — nothing crashes, nothing is lost, it
# just never actually reaches Resend until this is set.
#
# Client invoicing round (BUILD-SPEC.md "Phillip's ideas list — 6 July
# 2026" item 5): client invoice sends (POST /api/client-invoices/[id]/
# send) reuse this SAME RESEND_API_KEY via the shared transport in
# lib/resend.ts, just with a different from-address
# ('RESLU <accounts@reslu.com.au>' instead of visits@) and a PDF
# attachment. No separate env var needed — same no-op-until-set
# behaviour applies to invoice sends too.
#
# Lead flow round (migration 048) — FROM-ADDRESS CHANGE: lead-visit
# emails (visit-confirmation.html / visit-reminder.html, sent for BOTH
# lead site visits and project client_events) now send as
# 'Aria — RESLU <aria@reslu.com.au>' (superseding the r15 round's
# original 'Phillip — RESLU <visits@reslu.com.au>' identity), per
# docs/RESLU-lead-flow-brief.md's "Sending" section. Same
# RESEND_API_KEY, same Resend account/verified domain — no new key
# needed, this is a sender-identity swap only (see lib/visit-
# emails.ts's RESEND_FROM constant for the full write-up). Reply-To
# stays phillip@reslu.com.au, unchanged.
RESEND_API_KEY=
# Signing secret from the Resend webhook configured to POST to
# https://spec.reslu.com.au/api/trade-request/email-events. Required
# for durable delivered/opened/clicked/bounced booking-email evidence.
RESEND_WEBHOOK_SECRET=

# ── Stripe (optional — client invoice payment links) ──────────
# BUILD-SPEC.md "Phillip's ideas list — 6 July 2026" item 5 DECISIONS:
# "optional Stripe payment link per invoice for small invoices ...
# Stripe account setup is Phillip's task (never Claude's/Aria's —
# financial account)." Creating the Stripe account AND generating this
# secret key are both on-machine steps for Phillip — never automated.
# Used by POST /api/client-invoices/[id]/stripe-link (plain fetch to
# Stripe's REST API, no SDK dependency, matching this codebase's Resend
# integration's own "no SDK" convention) — a PLAIN fetch call, never
# auto-triggered on invoice create/send. Unset = the "Create payment
# link" button simply doesn't appear in the Client invoices composer,
# and Settings shows "Stripe payment links: not configured". Bank
# transfer (see the "Client invoicing setup" section of README.md)
# remains the standard payment method regardless — this is an optional
# add-on for design-fee-sized amounts only, never construction-sized
# ones (card fees are prohibitive at that scale).
STRIPE_SECRET_KEY=

# ── Web push (Health + web push round, r26) ────────────────────
# VAPID key pair for payload-less browser push (public/sw.js,
# lib/push.ts) — see docs/MINI-HEALTH-HANDOFF.md §6 for the exact
# node:crypto one-liner that generates both values below (no web-push
# npm dependency — package.json was checked, it isn't present, so this
# round implements RFC 8292 VAPID signing directly on node:crypto).
# NEXT_PUBLIC_VAPID_PUBLIC_KEY is also read client-side (build-time
# public env) by components/settings/PushSettings.tsx as the
# `applicationServerKey` for pushManager.subscribe(). Unset = the
# Settings "Push notifications" section shows "not configured" and
# lib/push.ts's sendPushToAdmins silently no-ops (same "no-op until
# configured" posture as RESEND_API_KEY above) — nothing crashes,
# pushes just never go out until both are set.
NEXT_PUBLIC_VAPID_PUBLIC_KEY=
VAPID_PRIVATE_KEY=

# ── Mini (Aria's Mac mini) health scripts ───────────────────────
# NOT read by this Next.js app itself — same shape as the existing
# "Aria (OpenClaw agent)" section above (SPEC_URL/ARIA_EMAIL/
# ARIA_PASSWORD, already defined there, are reused as-is). Documented
# here only as a pointer: docs/MINI-HEALTH-HANDOFF.md is the full spec
# for the mini-side heartbeat/channel-status/diagnostics scripts —
# launchd plist, env vars each script needs (SPEC_URL + the Supabase
# URL/anon key + ARIA_EMAIL/ARIA_PASSWORD, all already listed in this
# file), the vercel.json cron line CC needs to add, and the VAPID
# keygen one-liner above. No new env var name is introduced for the
# mini beyond the two VAPID ones above.
